<div class="slide">
    <h1>Why is Whitespace important?</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Remember: Indentation is syntactically significant</li>
        <li>It defines code blocks (classes, functions, etc)</li>
        <ul><li>So it matters!</li></ul>
        <ul><li>You need consistency.</li></ul>
    </ul>    
</div>

<div class="slide">
    <h1>Whitespace Settings for Python</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Spaces and tabs can be mixed.</li>
            <ul><li>Then a tab is equivalent to 8 space columns</li></ul>
            <ul><li>But this is a recipe for confusion</li></ul>
        <li>We recommend:</li>
            <ul><li>Always expanding tabs.</li></ul>
            <div class='handout'>This means that tabs will always be converted straight into spaces</div>
            <ul><li>Using tab stops of 4 spaces.</li></ul>
        <li>Set up your editor accordingly.</li>
        <li>Always expand tabs when importing foreign sources.</li>
    </ul>


<div class="slide">
    <h1>Editors</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Use whatever you're comfortable with</li>
        <ul>
        <li>Make sure you can configure it to meet Python whitespace needs</li>
        </ul>
        <li>We're supporting two for this course</li>
        <li>vim</li>
            <ul>
                <li>Console based, modal editor - you love it or hate it</li>
                <li>What we all use at work, so what we're most familiar with</li>
            </ul>
        <li>scite - Scintilla Text Editor</li>
            <ul>
            <li>can be set up for many languages</li>
            <li>particularly good for Python</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Handles indentation very well</li>
                </ul>
            <li>available for MS Windows</li>
            <li>Scintilla is used by eric, a Python IDE</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>eric is written with PyQt</li>
                </ul>
            </ul>
        <div class='handout'>
        <ul>
            <li>Cross platform ones (eric, eclipse?...) </li>
            <li>configurability etc - general config issues </li>
            <li>specific config for vim and scite</li>
        </ul>
        </div>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide"> 
    <h1>Writing and Running Scripts    </h1>

    <ul>
        <li>Python scripts are normally written in files with names ending in .py</li>
        <li>Scripts are executed using the <i>python</i> command</li>
    </ul> 
    <div class='handout'>
        <ul>
            <li>Open Command Prompt, [text-editor] simple.py</li>
            <li>Type in a simple program, with mistakes, save and run:</li>
            <li>
<pre>
while Number &lt; 10:
      Number += 1
      print Number
</pre>
            </li>
            <li>Run it first like this:   python simple.py</li>
            <li>See the error, add the line 'Number = 0' or whatever, and try again. </li>
            <li>Now change its mode to executable, 755, and try running it directly, as  'simple.py'.</li>
            <li>Edit it again with <tt>#!/usr/bin/env python</tt> at beginning.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
